INT. FIRST PLAINS BANK, BROKEN BOW, NEBRASKA - DAY

Fluorescent light, carpet tiles, one teller window open. A cardboard sign on an easel by the door: THE STEWARDSHIP ACT — WORKING FOR COMMUNITIES LIKE YOURS. Nobody is looking at it.

CRICKET DAWES, 79, sits in the waiting area. Pressed white shirt, buttoned to the collar. A manila folder square on his knees, both hands on it.

INT. LOAN OFFICE - DAY

The LOAN OFFICER, 30s, tie too new, is on the desk phone as Cricket comes in. He waves him to the chair, mouths sorry.

OFFICER:
(into phone)
— no, the culvert's the county's. That's not ours, tell him to call Roads. Roads. R-O— I have to go.

He hangs up. Exhales. Checks a sticky note on his monitor.

OFFICER:
Mr. Dawes. Sorry. Everybody's got a flooded something this week.

Cricket sets the folder on the desk and opens it. Tab dividers, fifty years of order. He slides the county letter across.

OFFICER:
I've got it on screen, you don't need—

Cricket slides the assessment appeal receipt across too. The officer takes it to be polite and sets it down without reading it.

CRICKET:
County reassessed in March. Four thousand two hundred six dollars, due the fifteenth. I have two thousand one hundred.

OFFICER:
(typing)
Okay. So there was a program for exactly this. Hardship deferral on ag-adjacent parcels, it's — hang on.

He reads his screen. Half to himself, losing the thread of it:

OFFICER:
"Suspended pending alignment review of county remittance instruments under the" — um. It's paused. Not paused — there's no — there isn't a mechanism right now. Is what that means.

CRICKET:
When does it come back?

OFFICER:
It doesn't say. It's federal now. The language doesn't — it doesn't say.

A silence. The officer scrolls Cricket's accounts, filling it.

OFFICER:
You've banked here — wow. Sixty-one years. That's longer than my dad's been alive.

He stops scrolling. Squints.

ON HIS SCREEN: a recurring deposit line. NASA — $0.00 QUARTERLY. Account description: DAWES, E. — ASTRONAUT (ACTIVE).

OFFICER:
There's a deposit here from NASA. Every quarter. For zero dollars and zero cents. That's got to be a glitch, I can put a ticket in and get it scrubbed off your—

CRICKET:
Leave it.

Too fast. Too hard. The officer looks up. Cricket sits exactly as he was, level again.

CRICKET:
It's been there fifty years. It can stay.

OFFICER:
...Sure.

He closes that window. Sits back. Thinks. Then he pulls a form from the drawer and talks while he fills it in, not looking up.

OFFICER:
What I can do is — our scanner's been down, there's a whole tray of stuff that hasn't been logged, things get received when they get received —

He stamps a date box.

OFFICER:
— so your paperwork came in next cycle. That's sixty days before anything goes delinquent. Don't tell my branch manager.

He slides the carbon copy across.

OFFICER:
Or do, honestly. She does it too.

Cricket looks at the stamp. Puts the copy in the folder, in order, and stands.

CRICKET:
What do I owe you?

OFFICER:
It's a bank, Mr. Dawes. You owe us four thousand dollars.

A beat. Almost a smile out of Cricket. He squares the folder under his arm and stops at the door, half turned.

CRICKET:
Your culvert caller. If that's the one under Route 12 by the Hollen place, that's county, he's right. But Roads won't get to it till October. Log chain and a tractor, some Saturday. Hour of work.

Cricket's already turning for the door. He lifts two fingers off the folder and doesn't look back.

OFFICER:
(watching him go, something shifting)
...I'll pass that on. [beat] Every quarter, huh.

Cricket goes.

EXT. FIRST PLAINS BANK, PARKING LOT - DAY

Cricket sits in his pickup, folder on the bench seat, keys in his hand. Through the windshield: the courthouse across the square, and above it, the flag, moving.

He watches it one moment. Then, alone, he lets his shoulders down half an inch and breathes out long, like he's been holding it since before the meeting started.

CRICKET:
(to himself, dry)
"Working for communities like yours."

He almost laughs. Doesn't, quite. Starts the truck.

CUT TO:
